Herein, we introduced a small amount of Li6.5La3Zr1.5Ta0.5O12 ceramic particles (LLZTO) into a polymer matrix composed of PDOL and poly(ethylene glycol) diacrylate (PEGDA) oligomers with DME as a plasticizer, and synthesized a novel composite electrolyte (LL-GCE) via in-situ thermal polymerization of PEGDA. On the premise that the polymerization of DOL triggered by lithium difluoro(oxalate)borate (LiDFOB) can increase the salt concentration, the LLZTO additives can synergistically enhance the dissociation of lithium salts through electrostatic interactions with PEGDA. As a result, favorable anion-rich solvation configurations are constructed in LL-GCE with a significantly improved ionic conductivity (7.9 × 10−4 S cm−1). Benefiting from the unique solvation structure, LL-GCE simultaneously exhibits outstanding Li compatibility and high-voltage cathode adaptation with Li+ transference number drastically raised to 0.83, which is almost the highest among reported ether-based gel electrolytes (
                        Table S1
                     ). Specifically, the symmetrical Li||Li cell with LL-GCE can be stably operated for over 2000 h at 0.1 mA cm−2. The LiFePO4 (LFP)||Li full cell delivers a high capacity of 135.4mAh/g with an ultrahigh capacity retention of 99.3 % after 250 cycles at 1C. When coupled with a high-voltage LiCoO2 (LCO) cathode, the LCO||Li battery also exhibits excellent electrochemical performance. The results of this work show a broad application prospect of the well-designed LL-GCE electrolyte in the next-generation SSLBs.
